slidetranscripts.Text:
This sample e-learning is from a more extensive course on the International Council for Harmonisation of Technical Requirements for Pharmaceuticals for Human Use, known as ICH for short. The focus of this sample segment is the 13 Core Principles of ICH E6, which provides guidance for the conduct of clinical trials in accordance with Good Clinical Practice. Remember that the E stands for efficacy which is defined as the power to produce a desired result or effect. For clinical trials, the desired outcome is to produce data of high quality and integrity and ensure patient safety.

The ICH E6 13 Core Principles offer guidance to help us balance different and sometimes conflicting needs and constraints, and navigate the grey areas we may encounter in order to achieve our objectives ethically and with integrity. But just as values or requirements can sometimes conflict with each other, we encounter situations, during the course of a clinical trial, in which different principles can lead us to different, sometimes conflicting responses.

As you review each of the 13 Core Principles covered here, please consider situation in which decisions may require balancing one, or several conflicting principles, and what criteria might be involved in finding the safest and most effective balance.

The first principle is about the overall conduct of clinical trials. It states that clinical trials should be conducted in accordance with ethical principles that have their origin in the Declaration of Helsinki, and are consistent with Good Clinical Practice and applicable regulatory requirements. This declaration is generally seen as the basis for clinical trial ethics, and, in 1964, was still largely shaped by discoveries of the medical experiments conducted on prisoners during the Second World War. Two foundational values from the Declaration of Helsinki that have far-reaching impacts on the conduct of clinical trials are to put the well-being of patients over all other interests and the importance of respect for the individual, and to each persons right to self-determination and to the ability to make informed decisions. This is the basis for the informed consent requirements that are fundamental requirements for our clinical trials.

The second principle is about balancing risks and benefits. It states that before a trial is initiated, foreseeable risks and inconveniences should be weighed against the anticipated benefit for the individual trial subject and society. And that a trial should be initiated and continued only if the anticipated benefits justify the risks.

The third principle clarifies the value of benefits to science and society, versus that placed on the individual trial subjects, indicating that subjects take priority. It states that the rights, safety and wellbeing of the trial subjects are the most important considerations and should prevail over interests of science and society.

The fourth principle considers what information is needed to justify running a clinical trial. It says the available non-clinical and clinical information on an investigational product should be adequate to support the proposed clinical trial.
The fifth principle focuses on how trials are planned and run. Clinical trials should be scientifically sound, following the scientific method, and described in a clear, detailed protocol.

The sixth principle addresses the alignment of protocols developed for studies with ethical practices. It states that a trial should be conducted in compliance with a protocol that has received prior institutional review board or independent ethics committee approval or favorable opinion before the trial begins.

The seventh principle is about who is responsible for medical care and medical decisions and says that medical care given to, and medical decision made on behalf of subjects should always be the responsibility of a qualified physician or, when appropriate, of a qualified dentist.

Please write, in a few sentences or a short paragraph, what might be some issues faced by a Principal Investigator when medical care decisions for an enrolled subject might conflict or deviate from the study protocol. Click the check mark on the bottom right of your screen when finished.

The eighth principle considers the qualifications of people, other than physicians or dentists, in conducting clinical trials: It states that each individual involved in conducting a trial should be qualified by education, training, and experience to perform his or her respective task(s).

In the ninth principle Informed Consent is addressed. This principle states that freely given informed consent should be obtained from every subject prior to clinical participation. However, as new information or new discoveries change the study design, or alter the risks and benefits of a clinical trial, ensuring subjects remain informed of these changes, and consent to continued participation, is required on an ongoing basis).

In E6, in section 4.8.10, is a full listing of all the information ICH indicates should be included, verbally and in writing, as part of the Informed Consent process.

The tenth principle deals how clinical trial information should be managed, and states that all clinical trial information should be recorded, handled and stored in a way that allows its accurate reporting, interpretation and verification.

We know that medical records often contain information that is highly sensitive to subjects and to their families, so policies and procedures that maintain confidentiality and privacy are needed. Thats the focus of the eleventh principle, that the confidentiality of records that could identify subjects should be protected, respecting the privacy and confidentiality rules in accordance with applicable regulatory requirement(s).

As we work globally, its important to keep in mind that different cultures and countries can have differing ideas about what information is considered private and confidential and we be aware and respectful of those differences.

The twelfth principle focuses on requirements for the investigational products. According to this principle, investigational products should be manufactured, handled and stored in accordance with applicable Good Manufacturing Practice, and used in accordance with the approved protocol.

That brings us to the final GCP Core Principle, which is about maintaining quality, an underlying goal of every stage of our work. This 13th Principle states that systems with procedures that assure quality of every aspect of the trial should be implemented.
Thank you for your time and attention to this sample of my work.
